<h1>@HI{{mono}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <strong>@HI{{mono}}</strong>.
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{mono}}</strong> is a sentence ending particle that, in a vague way, means "because" or "the reason is".
</p>

<p>
It can indicate an excuse. This usage is mostly employed by women.
</p>

<p>
It can indicate dissatisfaction, and is mostly used in this way by women.
</p>

<p>
It can indicate a desire to be indulged or pampered.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{reflect^brush-stroke}}ha@KJ{{mask^white}}kunaindesu<strong>mono</strong>. dakara,@KJ{{going}}kanakattanoyo.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      That film is simply too boring. That's why I didn't go.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{bamboo^inside}}sanha@KJ{{one^thong}}ni@KJ{{attend^matter}}woshitakunainoyo. chittomo@KJ{{work}}
      nainda<strong>mono</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I don't want to work with Takeuchi. He just doesn't work.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{exit}}kakemashouyo. tamaniha@KJ{{outside}}de@KJ{{eat^matter}}gashitaindesu<strong>mono</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Come on, let's go out. I'd like to eat out once in a while.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

